5–Deceased","1517–Female":"1517–Deceased","1515–1613":"1515–1613","1515–Female":"1515–Deceased","1535–1614":"1535–1614","1487–1527":"1487–1527","1479–1593":"1479–1593","1593":"1593","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1513":"1513","1535":"1535","1512":"1512","1479":"1479","1533":"1533","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1487":"1487","1585":"1585","1508":"1508","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","1527":"1527","1614":"1614","1515":"1515","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Prysawe, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dalton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: habitational name from any of various places called Dalton in Westmorland, Durham, Lancashire, Northumberland, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>dæl</i> ‘valley’ (see   Dale  ) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","History: The surname was taken to Ireland by English traders in the early 13th century ."],"variants":[{"name":"Daughton","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire) and Irish (Kilkenny and Tipperary): variant of   Dalton  ."]},{"name":"Dale","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>dal</i>, <i>dale</i>, <i>daile</i> ‘dale, valley’ (Old English <i>dæl</i>, reinforced in northern England by the cognate Old Norse <i>dalr</i>), a topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, or a habitational name from any of numerous minor places called with this word, such as Dale in Cumbria and Yorkshire.","Norwegian: habitational name from a common farm named from Old Norse <i>dali</i>, the dative case of <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’.","Americanized form of German   Diehl  ."]},{"name":"Dolton","meanings":["English: variant of   Dalton  ."]},{"name":"Daulton","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Dalton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":36,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":45,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":72,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":74,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":107,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When William Dalton was born in 1513, in England, his father, Sir Roger Dalton, was 27 and his mother, Anne Radcliffe, was 34. He married Jane Townley in 1533, in England."},"et":{"1513–":"1513–Surnud","1508–Male":"1508–Surnud","1513–Male":"1513–Surnud","1515–Male":"1515–Surnud","1517–Female":"1517–Surnud","1515–1613":"1515–1613","1515–Female":"1515–Surnud","1535–1614":"1535–1614","1487–1527":"1487–1527","1479–1593":"1479–1593","1593":"1593","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1513":"1513","1535":"1535","1512":"1512","1479":"1479","1533":"1533","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1487":"1487","1585":"1585","1508":"1508","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","1527":"1527","1614":"1614","1515":"1515","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Prysawe, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1513–":"1513–Kuollut","1508–Male":"1508–Kuollut","1513–Male":"15